  "title": "Die Erreichbarkeit der Gesellschaft",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "56f47adaeb5f22c6",
      "text": "FUCHS, Peter, 1992. [[Die Erreichbarkeit der Gesellschaft]]: zur Konstruktion und Imagination gesellschaftlicher Einheit. Frankfurt am Main: Suhrkamp. ISBN 978-3-518-58109-4"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "db1ceba81e73277b",
      "text": "(Post-)modern society appears to be multi-perspectival or, as one might put it with reference to [[Gotthard Günther]], polycontextual. There are apparently no excellent vantage points, no privileged standpoints from which social or psychological \"facts\" can be grasped ontologically. What is observed in one place and from one place may be observed differently in other places and from other places. There is no [[Archimedean Point]] from which arbitrary observations can be detached, compared, and transformed into each other on the basis of social or psychological invariances."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c70d611778a56602",
      "text": "This has far-reaching epistemological consequences, e.g. that one has to come to terms with the idea of plural epistemologies (and thus plural ontologies) and see the realization of that \"polemical totality\" of which Hardenberg/Schlegelian symphilosophy developed the first ideas and postmodernism the preceding ones. As long as this process of disorientation takes place at the level of science, it can perhaps be ignored or even treated as a resource for ever new problem possibilities. After all, assuming polycontexturality, there will never be an end to science: One only has to observe differently in order to arrive at other realities."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0514e46e0f587965",
      "text": "It seems, however, that this process does not only affect the sciences. It is society that begins to describe itself as a \"polemical totality\", as multi-perspectival, as hyper-complex. The disorientation of the individuals, the uncontrollability of social systems, crises of meaning and relevance, the loss of grand narratives (Lyotard) are common topoi in this context, and it is a typically lamenting topoi, referring above all to the postmodern brokenness of the individual or to the failure of what used to be called the individual or the subject altogether. One can then demand a kind of [[Restoration]] of what has been lost, and/or aestheticize the lament and thus wrest some pleasure from the seemingly apocalyptic labyrinth of meaning of postmodernism, and/or construct communalist enclaves of meaning in which mutual affirmations and common limitations of the possibilities of observation become the leaders of the exclusion of other possibilities of observation."
    }
